#Text=3. Parturition and Neonatal Oxygenation

#Text=Oxygen deprivation during parturition , as the main cause of stillbirth , may be caused by stretching and even rupture of the umbilical cord during stage II ( expulsion of piglets ) of parturition .
#Text=However , the cumulative effect of repeated contractions compressing the placenta and reducing blood flow to the foetus is probably more important .
#Text=Obstruction of blood flow to the foetus induces a temporary drop in heart rate , which in itself is probably harmless and an adaptive mechanism of the foetus to reduce its oxygen consumption .

#Text=Repeated episodes of obstructed blood flow , however , can result in anaerobic metabolism , the cumulative effect of which is an increasing lactate level in foetal blood and a decreasing foetal blood pH as buffering capacity is exhausted .

#Text=This was demonstrated by van Dijk , et al. , who clamped the umbilical cord of unborn piglets for 5 – 8 min during caesarean section , to simulate the cumulative effect of oxygen insufficiency .

#Text=In observational studies with no interventions , the cumulative effect of oxygen deprivation is reflected in the profound effect of birth order on asphyxia symptoms , with piglets later in the birth order showing increasingly higher lactate and lower pH in umbilical cord samples at birth .
#Text=In a more recent study , the total duration of farrowing was shown to exacerbate the effect of birth order on measures of asphyxia and on the risk of stillbirth .
#Text=This explains why stillbirth rate increases with birth order (
#Text=Figure 2
#Text=) , especially in sows that experience a prolonged duration of farrowing .
#Text=From this , it is questionable whether birth intervals contribute to stillbirth , as is sometimes suggested .

#Text=In fact , a recent study showed that risk of stillbirth only started to increase significantly when birth interval exceeded 90 min , whereas the duration of farrowing increased the risk cumulatively with every 2 h that elapsed .

#Text=The importance of the cumulative effect of contractions is supported by observations from Zerobin and Kündig , showing that inhibition of contractions at the start or just before parturition , using a tocolytic , prolonged parturition without increasing stillbirths .
#Text=It is not clear how exactly the mechanics of foetal expulsion work in the pig .
#Text=Both tubo-cervical and cervico-tubal contractions occur during parturition , the first obviously serving to transport foetuses to the birth canal .

#Text=The function of the latter is less clear , but have been proposed to shorten the uterine horn and to prevent accumulation of foetuses at the caudal end , thus reducing the premature rupture of the umbilical cord .

#Text=In this respect , we do not know whether before being expelled , foetuses gradually travel through the uterine horn , or remain positioned at their implantation site and only travel to the birth canal once it is their turn .
#Text=These two scenarios have different implications for the oxygenation for the foetus .

#Text=In prolonged parturitions , placentae may also start to detach , since van Rens and van der Lende reported that in contrast to short parturitions where placentae are expelled after the last piglet has been born , in prolonged parturitions the first set of membranes are expelled while some piglets are still to be born .

#Text=With the cumulative duration of farrowing and birth order being the predominant factors determining the risk of stillbirth , other piglet-related factors that increase this risk are a ruptured umbilical cord , breech position and meconium staining .

#Text=It is interesting to note that the percentage of piglets born with a ruptured umbilical cord varies widely from around 20 % to 70 % , and also that in some studies this percentage increases with birth order , whereas in others it is constant .
#Text=Around 50 % or more of stillbirths are associated with a ruptured umbilical cord , which suggests that this is an important risk factor .
#Text=However , when expressed as the relative risk , a ruptured umbilical cord increases the risk of stillbirth approximately three-fold .
#Text=This is much less compared to birth order and length of parturition .

#Text=In short parturitions ( <3 h for example ) , stillbirth increased ten-fold between the first and the last piglets in the birth order ; in long parturitions , stillbirth increased forty-fold ( from 1 % to 37 % ) between the first and the last piglets .
#Text=The same applies to meconium staining which occurs frequently and increases the relative risk by around three-fold .
#Text=With meconium staining it is also difficult to assess whether it is a consequence of asphyxia , or whether it contributed to the factors leading up to stillbirth .
#Text=According to Randall , posterior delivery is a physiological condition in pigs and not associated with increased risk of stillbirth .
